        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    
  </example>

  <p>
    If your function is one-to-one, then flipping the arrows gives you a <em>new</em> function that <em>undoes</em> your original function. 
    That new function is called the <term>inverse</term> of the original function.  
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-inverse">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be a one-to-one function.
        Its <term>inverse</term> is the function, written <m>f^{-1}</m>, which satisfies 
        <md>
          <mrow> f(x)   =    y </mrow>
          <mrow>      \iff      </mrow>
          <mrow>  x     =    f^{-1}(y) </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    In <xref ref="eg_onetoone"/>, the function <m>f</m> has an inverse function <m>f^{-1}</m>, defined by flipping each of the arrows. 
    For example, because <m>f(2) = c</m>, we have <m>f^{-1}(c) = 2</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Danger Zone:</alert>
      In general, the inverse <m>f^{-1}</m> is <alert>not</alert> the same thing as the reciprocal.  In other words, <m>f^{-1}(x)</m> is <alert>not</alert> <m>\dfrac{1}{f(x)}</m> in general.
  </p>

  <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-inverses">
    <title>Key Idea</title>
    <p>
      Inverse functions swich the roles of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> (of input and ouput). 
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <example>
    <title>Understanding Inverses Graphically</title>
     <p>
      Graphically, reversing the roles of input and ouput is the same thing as reflecting the graph of the function across the diagonal line <m>y=x</m>.
    </p>

    <image xml:id="img_graphinginverses">
      
      
