  </example>
 
  <p>
    Recall that the function <m>f^{-1}</m> <em>undoes</em> <m>f(x)</m>.
    Mathematically, this means 
    <me>
      f\Big( f^{-1}(x) \Big) = x
    </me>
    and 
    <me>
      f^{-1}\Big( f(x) \Big) = x
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    Finding inverses and solving equations are two sides of the same coin. 
  </p>
  <exploration>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x) = 2x+1</m>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find an equation for <m>f^{-1}(x)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, write down the equation <m>y=f(x)</m>.  In this case, 
          <me>
            y = 2x + 1
          </me>
          Next, solve this equation for <m>x</m>.  
          <md>
            <mrow> \amp y \amp \amp= \amp 2x \amp + 1 </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp   \amp -1 \amp \amp \amp -1 </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp y \amp -1 \amp= \amp 2x \amp  </mrow>
            
            <mrow> \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp </mrow>

            <mrow> \amp (y \amp -1)\amp= \amp (2x) \amp  </mrow>
            <mrow>  \times\frac{1}{2} \amp   \amp \amp \amp \amp \times\frac{1}{2} </mrow>
            <mrow> \frac{1}{2}\amp (y \amp -1)\amp= \amp x \amp  </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, reverse the roles of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.  This gives the equation 
          <me>
            y = \frac{1}{2} ( x - 1) = 0.5 x -0.5
          </me>
          The equation for our inverse is 
          <me>
            f^{-1}(x) = 0.5 x -0.5
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use your equation for <m>f^{-1}</m> to evaluate <m>f\Big(f^{-1}(x)\Big)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We are given that <m>\color{blue} f({\color{red} x}) = 2{\color{red} x} + 1</m>.  We have also found that <m>f^{-1}(x) = 0.5x - 0.5</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          To compute <m>{ \color{blue} f\Big({\color{red} f^{-1}(x)}\Big) }</m>, replace every <m>\color{red} x</m> in the equation for <m>\color{blue} f({\color{red} x}) </m> with the equation <m>\color{red} f^{-1}(x) = 0.5x - 0.5</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow> { \color{blue} f\Big({\color{red} f^{-1}(x)}\Big) }= \amp {\color{blue} f\Big( { \color{red} 0.5x - 0.5}\Big)}</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp {\color{blue}  2\cdot \Big({ \color{red} 0.5x - 0.5}\Big) + 1}</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp 2\cdot 0.5x - 2\cdot 0.5 + 1</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp 2\cdot 0.5x - 2\cdot 0.5 + 1</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp x - 1 + 1</mrow>
            <mrow>= \amp x</mrow>
          </md>
          We have shown in this case that <m>f\Big(f^{-1}(x)\Big)=x</m>.  
          In other words, we have shown that the function and inverse undo eachother.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec_logartims">
  <title>Logarithms Undo Exponentials</title>
  
  <p>
    Our main goal is to use logarithms to solve for time in a compound interest equation.  
    Those equations involve many parts, so we will start with a few slightly simpler questions, in the form of a riddle.
  </p>

  <exploration xml:id="ex_motivatinglogs">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many times do you need to double the number <m>10</m> to achieve an eight-fold increase?  
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Just start doubling 10, and see what works!
          <md>
            <mrow> 10 \cdot 2 = 20 </mrow>
            <mrow> 10 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 40 </mrow>
            <mrow> 10 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 80 </mrow>
          </md>
          You need to double 10 <em>three times</em> to get from 10 to 80 (an eight-fold increase).
          In other words, 
          <me>
            80 = 10 \cdot 2^3
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many times do you need to double any number <m>P</m> to achieve an eight fold increase of <m>P</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Our strategy for the first example works the same here:
          <md>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 2 = 2 P </mrow>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 4 P </mrow>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 2 \cdot 2 \cdot 2 = 8 P  </mrow>
          </md>
          You need to double any number <em>three times</em> to get an eight-fold increase.
          This is the same as saying that , 
          <me>
            8 =  2^3
          </me>
          
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many times do you need to triple <m>P</m> to get an 81-fold increase? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Our strategy for the first example works the same here:
          <md>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 3 = 3 P </mrow>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 3 \cdot 3 = 9 P </mrow>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 3\cdot 3 \cdot 3 = 21 P</mrow>
            <mrow>  P \cdot 3\cdot 3 \cdot 3 \cdot 3 = 81 P</mrow>
          </md>
          You need to triple any number <em>four times</em> to get an eighty one-fold increase.
          This is the same as saying that , 
          <me>
            81 =  3^4
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    <term>Logarithms</term> are functions that answer the riddle "how many times do I need to multiply by a number <m>b</m>" to increase by a given factor. More precisely, we make the following definition.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-logs">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given any numbers <m>b,x>0</m>, 
        <me>
          \log_{\color{blue}b}(x) = {\color{red} r}
        </me>
        is equal to the exponent <m>r</m> such that 
        <me>
          {\color{blue}b}^{\color{red} r} = x
        </me>
        
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    We can now rephrase <xref ref="ex_motivatinglogs"/> in logarithmic language. 
    Because <m>8 = {\color{blue}2}^{\color{red}3}</m>, we say that <m>\log_{\color{blue} 2}(8) = {\color{red}3}</m>.
    Similarly, because <m>81 = {\color{blue}3}^{\color{red}4}</m>, we say that <m>\log_{\color{blue} 3} (81) = {\color{red}4}</m>.
    More precisely, we can now answer the following question. 
  </p>
  
  <exploration xml:id="ex_computinglogs">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\log_2(8)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Written in exponential form, finding <m>\log_2(8) = r</m> is the same as finding the exponent <m>r</m> such that 
          <me>
            2^r = 8
          </me>
          Here, because <m>8 = {\color{blue}2}^{\color{red}3}</m>, we say that <m>\log_{\color{blue} 2}(8) = {\color{red}3}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\log_3(81)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Written in exponential form, finding <m>\log_3(31) = r</m> is the same as finding the exponent <m>r</m> such that 
          <me>
            3^r = 81
          </me>
          Here, because <m>81 = {\color{blue}3}^{\color{red}4}</m>, we say that <m>\log_{\color{blue} 3} (81) = {\color{red}4}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\log_{10}(1,000,000,000)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Written in exponential form, finding <m>\log_10(1,000,000,000) = r</m> is the same as finding the exponent <m>r</m> such that 
          <me>
            10^r = 1,000,000,000
          </me>
          To get the right hand side, we must multiply 10 nine times.  That means <m>1,000,000,000 = {\color{blue}10}^{\color{red}9}</m>.  Therefore, we have that <m>\log_{\color{blue} 10} (1,000,000,000) = {\color{red}9}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>


  <proposition xml:id="prop-logsareinverses">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Fix any base <m>b>1</m>.
        The function <m>y = \log_b(x)</m> is the inverse of the the base <m>b</m> exponential function <m>exp_b(x) = b^x</m>.  
      </p>
    </statement>
