  <paragraphs xml:id="subsec-naturallogs">
    <title>The Natural Logarithm for Calculus</title>
    
    <p>
      Recall that the function <m>y = e^x</m> is called the <em>natural exponential function</em>.  We call it's inverse the <term>natural logarithm</term>.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-naturallog">
      <statement>
        <p>
          We write <m>\ln(x) = \log_e(x)</m> where <m>e\approx 2.718\dots</m>
        </p>
        <p>
          In other words, the <term>natural logarithm</term> <m>y = \ln(x)</m> is the inverse of the natural exponential function <m>exp(x) = e^x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <exploration xml:id="ex_computingln">
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\ln(\sqrt{e})</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            There are two ways to answer this question.  Algebraically, we know that <m>\ln</m> undoes base <m>e</m> exponentiation.  So simply rewrite the argument of the function as a power of <m>e</m>
            <me>\ln(\sqrt{e}) = \ln(e^{1/2}) = \frac{1}{2}</me>
          </p>
          <p>
            Alternatively, you can answer the question by playing the riddle game: what does the exponent <m>r</m> of <m>e</m> need to be for <m>e^{r}</m> to equal <m>\sqrt{e}</m>?
          </p>
          <p>
            We know that <m>\sqrt{e} = e^{1/2}</m>.  In other words, we need the exponent of <m>e</m> to be <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.  That tells us that <m>\ln(\sqrt{e}) = \frac{1}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute <m>\ln\left(\dfrac{1}{e}\right)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Again, there are two ways to answer this question.  Algebraically, we know that <m>\ln</m> undoes base <m>e</m> exponentiation.  So simply rewrite the argument of the function as a power of <m>e</m>
            <me>\ln\left(\dfrac{1}{e}\right) = \ln(e^{-1}) = -1</me>
          </p>
          <p>
            Alternatively, you can answer the question by playing the riddle game: what does the exponent <m>r</m> of <m>e</m> need to be for <m>e^{r}</m> to equal <m>\frac{1}{e}</m>?
          </p>
          <p>
            We know that <m>\frac{1}{e} = e^{-1}</m>.  In other words, we need the exponent of <m>e</m> to be <m>-1</m>.  That tells us that <m>\ln\left(\dfrac{1}{e}\right) = -1</m>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
	<task>
	  <statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> and <m>g(x) = e^x</m>.
			Simplify <m>f(g(3))</m>, <m>f(g(-2))</m>, <m>f(g(45))</m>, and <m>f(g(x))</m>
		</p>
	  </statement>
	  <solution>
		<p>
			This is just a more complex way of asking us to simplify the natural log of e to various numbers.  
			Reasoning as above gives
			<me>f(g(3)) = \ln(e^3) = 3</me>
			<me>f(g(-2)) = \ln(e^{-2}) = -2</me>
			<me>f(g(45)) = \ln(e^{45}) = 45</me>
			<me>f(g(x)) = \ln(e^{x}) = x</me>
		</p>
	  </solution>
	</task>
    </exploration>
    
    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-naturalexplog">
      <title>Key Facts</title>
      <p>
        The functions <m>f(x) = \ln(x)</m> and <m>g(x) = exp(x) = e^x</m> <em>undo</em> eachother. 
        <md>
          <mrow> \ln\left(e^x\right) = x </mrow>
          <mrow> e^{\ln(x)} = x </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </assemblage>
  </paragraphs>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Simplify <m>e^{2\cdot \ln(5)}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>e^{2\cdot \ln(5)} = \amp e^{\ln(5)\cdot 2}      
                \amp \text{ Because } a^{rs} = a^{sr}    </mrow>
          <mrow>                  = \amp \Big(e^{\ln(5)}\Big)^2
                \amp \text{ Because } a^{rs} = (a^r)^{s} </mrow>
          <mrow>                  = \amp \Big(5\Big)^2         
                \amp  \text{ Because } e^{\ln(5)} = 5     </mrow>
          <mrow>                  = \amp 25                     
                \amp </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="sec-lawsoflogs">
  <title>Laws of Logarithms</title>
  
  <p>
    Logarithms have three important properties, which will play a central role in our computations.
  </p>

  <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-lawsoflogs">
    <title>Laws of Logarithms</title>
    <p>
      <me>
        \ln\Big( x^r \Big)= r\cdot \ln(x)
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>
        \ln\Big( x\cdot y \Big)= \ln(x) + \ln(y)
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>
        \ln\left( \dfrac{x}{y} \right)= \ln(x) - \ln(y)
      </me>
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <exploration xml:id="ex_usingloglaws">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Expand the following completely using the laws of logarithms.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ln(5^3)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> 
          When you look at this expression, you <em>see</em> a power, so <em>write</em> down the first law of logarithms <m>\ln\Big( x^r \Big)= r\cdot \ln(x)</m>.  Using the numbers we're given, we obtain
          <me>\ln(5^3) = 3\cdot \ln(5)</me>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\ln(10\cdot 5^3) </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          When you look at this expression, you <em>see</em> that the input is the product <m>10</m> and <m>5^3</m>, so <em>write</em> down the second law of logarithms <m>\ln\Big( x\cdot y \Big)= \ln(x) + \ln(y)</m>.   Applying that in our example, we get 
          <me>\ln(10\cdot 5^3) = \ln(10) + \ln( 5^3 )</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Recopy the first logarithm <m>\ln(10)</m>.  
          For the second logarithm, <em>see</em> that the input is a power, so <em>write</em> down the first law of logarithms <m>\ln\Big( x^r \Big)= r\cdot \ln(x)</m>.  That gives 
          <me>\ln(10\cdot 5^3) = \ln(10) + 3\cdot \ln( 5 )</me>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    <alert>Warning:</alert>
    Note that our three laws of logarithms only apply when the exponential, product, or fraction is <em>inside</em> the logarithm.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you try to divide logarithms, such as in <m> \dfrac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)}</m>, you will get something very different than our log laws.  
    This is because of the surprising fact that 
    <me>
      \log_b(x) = \dfrac{\ln(x)}{\ln(b)}
    </me>
    For example, if you divide   <m> \dfrac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)}</m>, you actually get 
    <m>
      \dfrac{\ln(5)}{\ln(2)} = \log_2(5) = 0.9162\dots
    </m>, which is <alert>not</alert> the same thing as <m>\ln\left(\frac{2}{5}
  \right)=0.4306\dots</m>.
  </p>
    
  <p>
    Again, for the remainder of the course, we will almost always restrict our attention to natural logarithms.  
    But this last property is useful in many applications, and may help you remember when you can (and when you can't) perform a simplification using the laws of logarithms. 
  </p>
    
    

</section>




<section xml:id="sec_solvingfortime">
  <title>Solving Compound Interest for Time</title>
  

  <p>
    We can now use the laws of logarithms to help us solve equations where the variable is in the exponent. 
  </p>
  <p>
    As with everything else in algebra, if we have the equation <m>A = B</m>, we can replace it with the equation <m>\ln(A) = \ln(B)</m>.
  </p>

  <exploration xml:id="ex_solving_exponentials">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>x</m> satisfying <m>2^{3x} = 5</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The key idea of algebra is that if you have the equation <m>A = B</m>, you can do the same thing to both sides and have another true equation.  
          Here, we are given that 
          <me>2^{3x} = 5</me>
          That means that we also know that the equation <m>\ln(A) = \ln(B)</m> is true, replacing <m>A=2^{3x}</m> and <m>B=5</m>.  This gives
          <me>
            \ln\Big(2^{3x}\Big) = \ln\Big( 5 \Big)
          </me>
          We have the property of logarithms that <m>\ln(x^r) = r\cdot\ln(x)</m> on the left, to get the equation 
          <me>
            3x \cdot \ln\Big(2\Big) = \ln\Big( 5 \Big)
          </me>
          Now, this looks complicated, but we can use a calculator to simplify <m>\ln(2) = 0.693\dots</m> and <m>\ln(5) = 1.609\dots</m>.  This gives us the equation 
          <me>
            3x \cdot 0.693{\dots} = 1.609\dots
          </me>
          Rearranging the left side, we have 
          <me>
            3\cdot 0.693{\dots}\cdot x = 1.609\dots
          </me>
          Using a calculator, we see that <m>3\cdot 0.693\dots = 2.079\dots</m>, which gives 
          <me>
            2.079\dots x = 1.609\dots 
          </me>
          Dividing both sides by <m>2.079\dots</m>, we get 
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{1.609\dots}{2.079\dots} = 0.773\dots
          </me>
          You could also have done this with the original <m>3x \cdot \ln\Big(2\Big) = \ln\Big( 5 \Big)</m> by dividing both sides by <m>3\cdot\ln(2)</m> to get 
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{\ln(5)}{3\cdot \ln(2)}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve for <m>x</m> satisfying <m>4\cdot(1.95)^{2x} = 16</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
        There are two different approaches for solving an equation like this, planning ahead or using brute force. 
          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>Planning Ahead</title>
              <p>
                We wish to solve the equation 
                <me>4\cdot(1.95)^{2x} = 16</me>
                We want to eventually introduce logarithms to allow us to apply Log Law 3, to pull the <m>2x</m> out of the exponent. 
                However, that law will not apply to <m>4\cdot (1.95)^{2x}</m> because of the coefficient of <m>4</m>. 
              </p>
              <p>
                But we can divide both sides of the equation by 4.  This gives us 
                <md>
                  <mrow> \amp 4\cdot (1.95)^{2x} \amp = \amp 16 \amp </mrow>
                  <mrow> \times\frac{1}{4} \amp \amp\amp \amp \times\frac{1}{4} </mrow>
                  <mrow> \amp (1.95)^{2x} \amp = \amp 4 \amp </mrow>
                </md>  
                Now, we can take the logarithm of both sides 
                <me>
                  \ln\Big( {\color{red}(1.95)}^{\color{blue}2x} \Big) = \ln\Big( 4 \Big)
                </me>
                Now we can apply the law of logs <m>\ln({\color{red}x}^{\color{blue}r})= {\color{blue}r}\ln({\color{red}x})</m> on the left with <m>\color{red} x = 1.95</m> and <m>\color{blue} r = 2x</m>
                <me>
                  {\color{blue} 2x} \cdot \ln\Big({\color{red} 1.95}\Big) = \ln\Big(4\Big)
                </me>
                We can now divide both sides by <m>2\cdot \ln(1.95)</m> to get 
                <me>
                  x = \dfrac{\ln\Big(4\Big)}{2\ln\Big(1.95\Big)}
                </me>
                This example is exact, but it can be a bit overwhelming.  You can also use your calculator to simplify 
                <md>
                  <mrow> 2x \cdot \ln\Big(1.95\Big) \amp = \ln\Big(4\Big) </mrow>
                  <mrow> </mrow>
                  <mrow> 2x \cdot 0.667\dots \amp = 1.386\dots </mrow>
                  <mrow> </mrow>
                  <mrow> x\cdot 1.335\dots  \amp = 1.386\dots</mrow>
                  <mrow> </mrow>
                  <mrow>x \amp = \dfrac{1.386\dots}{1.335\dots} = 1.038\dots</mrow>
                </md>

                If you do use your calculator, try to use as many decimal places as possible.  Rounding errors can grow if you do a lot of calculations.  It is possible to understand how these errors grow, but that question is beyond the scope of this course. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Brute Force</title>
              <p>
                We have seen how to solve this equation with a bit of planning ahead.  But what happens if you <em>start</em> by taking the natural log of both sides of the quation
                <me>4\cdot(1.95)^{2x} = 16</me>
                You get 
                <me>
                  \ln\Big( {\color{red} 4}\cdot{\color{blue} (1.95)^{2x}} \Big) = \ln\Big(16\Big)
                </me>
                On the left side, we have <m>\ln\Big( {\color{red} 4}\cdot{\color{blue} (1.95)^{2x}} \Big)</m>.  We <em>cannot</em> use Log Law 1, since this is a product.  Instead, we need to use Log Law 2 <m>\ln({\color{red} a}\cdot {\color{blue} b}) = \ln({\color{red} a}) + \ln({\color{blue} b})</m> with <m>\color{red} a=4</m> and <m>\color{blue} b=(1.95)^{2x}</m>.  This gives 
                <me>
                  \ln\Big( {\color{red} 4}\Big) + \ln\Big({\color{blue} (1.95)^{2x}} \Big) = \ln\Big(16\Big)
                </me>
                Now we can use Law Log 1 <m>\ln(a^r) = r\cdot \ln(a)</m> with <m>a=1.95</m> and <m>r=2x</m> to get 
                <me>
                  \ln\Big( { 4}\Big) + 2x\cdot \ln\Big({ (1.95)} \Big) = \ln\Big(16\Big)
                </me>
                You can simplify this using a calculator to get 
                <me>
                  {1.386\dots} + 2\cdot x\cdot 0.667\dots = 2.772\dots
                </me>
                You can solve this as usual to get
                <me>
                  x = \dfrac{{2.772\dots} - 1.386\dots}{2\cdot 0.667\dots} = 1.038\dots
                </me>
                Alternatively, you can solve the exact equation to get 
                <me>
                  x = \dfrac{\ln(16) - \ln(4)}{2\cdot \ln(1.95)}
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The balance of a certain investment is given by <m>F(t) = 10\cdot 2^t</m> as a function of the number of years <m>t</m>.  
          How long must you wait until the balance reaches 80?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Note that <em>this specific function</em> is very simple, so it is possible to answer this numerically.  After one year, the balance will be <m>F(1) = 20</m>, after two years the balance will be <m>F(2)=40</m>, and after three years the balance will be <m>F(3)=80</m>.   It will take 3 years for the balance to reach <m>80</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For more complex equations, we will need to set up and solve an exponential equation.  In this case, we want to find a <m>t</m> such that <m>F(t) = 10 \cdot 2^t</m> equals 80.
          This gives us the equation 
          <md>
            <mrow> 80 \amp=\amp 10 \cdot 2^t \amp </mrow>
            <mrow> 8 \amp=\amp 2^t \amp \qquad\text{ Multiply both sides by }\dfrac{1}{10}</mrow>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(8\Big) \amp=\amp \ln\Big(2^t\Big) \amp  \qquad\text{ Take }\ln\text{ of both sides}</mrow>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(8\Big) \amp=\amp t\cdot \ln\Big(2\Big) \amp \qquad\text{ Log Law 1 } \ln(a^r)=r\ln(a)</mrow>
            <mrow> \dfrac{\ln\Big(8\Big)}{\ln\Big(2\Big)} \amp=\amp t  \amp \qquad\text{ Divide both sides by } \ln\Big(2\Big)</mrow>
          </md>
          Alternatively, we could have simplified the natural log terms and solved as follows
          <md>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(8\Big) = t\cdot \ln\Big(2\Big) </mrow>
            <mrow> 2.079{\dots}= t\cdot {0.693\dots} </mrow>
            <mrow>t =  \dfrac{2.079{\dots}}{0.693\dots} = 3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    We can now apply these techinques to solve the equations that arise in questions of compound interest.
  </p>

  <exploration xml:id="ex_compoundinterestfortime">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        You invest $1000 at 15% interest compounded monthly.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How many years are required until you double your money?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, write down the compound interest formula from  <xref ref="def-compoundinterest"/>.
          <me>
            F = P\cdot \left(1 + \frac{r}{m}\right)^{mt}
          </me>
          with <m>P=1000</m>, <m>r=0.15</m>, and <m>m=12</m>.  
          Furthermore, we want the <em>future value</em>to be twice 1000.  In other words, we want <m>F=2000</m>
          This gives 
          <me>
            2000 = 1000 \cdot \left(1 + \dfrac{0.15}{12}\right)^{12t}
          </me>
          Dividing both sides by 1000 gives 
          <me>
            2 = \left(1 + \dfrac{0.15}{12}\right)^{12t}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Next, we can simplify this equation using a calculator and the <xref ref="exponential-arithmetic">properties of exponents</xref>
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> 2 = \amp \left(1 + \dfrac{0.15}{12}\right)^{12t} \amp </mrow>
            <mrow> 2 = \amp \left(\ 1.0125\ \right)^{12t} \amp </mrow>
            <mrow> 2 = \amp \left(\ 1.0125^{12}\ \right)^{t} \amp \qquad\text{Because } a^{rs}=(a^r)^s</mrow>
            <mrow> 2 = \amp \left(\ 1.16075\dots\ \right)^{t} \amp </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Finally, finish solving the exponential equation as above using the  <xref ref="assemblage-lawsoflogs" text="custom">Laws of Logs</xref>.
          <md>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(2\Big) = \amp \ln\Big( \left(\ 1.16075\dots\ \right)^{t} \Big) \amp </mrow>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(2\Big) = \amp t\cdot \ln\Big(  1.16075\dots \Big) \amp \qquad\text{Using }\ln(a^r) = r\ln(a)</mrow>
            <mrow>t = \amp \dfrac{ \ln\Big(2\Big)}{\ln\Big(  1.16075\dots \Big) }\amp \qquad\text{Dividing both sides by }\ln\Big(  1.16075\dots \Big)</mrow>
            <mrow>t = \amp 4.64\dots</mrow>
          </md>
          With 15% interest, it will take about 4.64 years for the balance to double.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How long will it be until the balance reaches $10,000?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, write down the compound interest formula 
            <me>
              F = P\cdot \left(1 + \frac{r}{m}\right)^{mt}
            </me>
          and plug in the values we are given.  Note that we want the time when the future value <m>F=10,000</m>.  That gives 
          <me>
            10,000 = 1,000 \cdot (1 + \frac{0.15}{12})^{12t}
          </me>
          Simplifying this with a calculator and the laws of exponents gives 
          <md>
            <mrow>10 \amp = (1 + \frac{0.15}{12})^{12t}</mrow>
            <mrow>10 \amp = (1.0125 )^{12t}</mrow>
            <mrow>10 \amp = (1.16075\dots )^{t}</mrow>
          </md>
          Taking <m>\ln</m> of both sides and applying the laws of logarithms, we get 
          <md>
            <mrow>\ln\Big(10\Big) \amp = \ln\Big( (1.16075\dots )^{t} \Big)</mrow>
            <mrow>\ln\Big(10\Big) \amp = t\cdot \ln\Big( 1.16075\dots  \Big)</mrow>
            <mrow>\dfrac{\ln\Big(10\Big)}{\ln\Big( 1.16075\dots  \Big)} \amp = t  </mrow>
            <mrow>t \amp = 14.868\dots \amp </mrow>
          </md>
          The balance will increase to $10,000 in about 15 years. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>

  <p>
    As an exercise, find how long it takes for a balance of $1000 to double at 2% interest, at 5% interest, and at 30% interest. 
  </p>

  <p>
    For our last application, we will return to the concept of <term>depreciation</term>, discussed in more depth in <xref ref="insight-depreciation"/> and <xref ref="ex_depreciation1"/>
  </p>

  <exploration xml:id="ex_depreciation2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Suppose that a certain asset loses 30% of its value each year. 
        In other words, suppose that the value of the asset after <m>t</m> years is given by 
        <me>
          V(t) = P\cdot (1-0.3)^t
        </me>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that  the asset starts with value <m>P=1000</m>. 
          Find the value after 12 years. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The future value function is 
          <me>
            V(t) = 1000 \cdot (1-0.3)^t = 1000\cdot 0.7^t
          </me>
          After <m>12</m> years, 
          <me>
            V(12) = 1000 \cdot (1-0.3)^{12} = 13.841
          </me>
          After <m>12</m> years, the value of the asset will be approximately $13.84
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the value after 12 years is $50.  Find the starting value <m>P</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The future value function is 
          <me>
            V = P \cdot (1-0.3)^t 
          </me>
          We know that when <m>t=12</m>, that <m>V=50</m>.  Plugging this in gives
          <md>
            <mrow>50 \amp = P \cdot (1-0.3)^{12}</mrow>
            <mrow>50 \amp = P \cdot 0.0138\dots</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{50}{0.138} \amp = P</mrow>
            <mrow>P \amp = 3612.380\dots</mrow>
          </md>
          The starting value must have been about $3,612.38
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that the asset starts with a value <m>P=1000</m>.  
          Find the number of years <m>t</m> for the value to decrease to <m>100</m>.  
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The future value function is 
          <me>
            V = P \cdot (1-0.3)^t 
          </me>
          We want the time <m>t</m> when the value reaches <m>V=100</m> when from a starting value of <m>P=1,000</m>.  Plugging this in gives
          <md>
            <mrow> 100 \amp = 1000 \cdot (0.7)^t</mrow>
            <mrow> 0.1 \amp =  (0.7)^t</mrow>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(0.1\Big) \amp =  \ln\Big((0.7)^t\Big)</mrow>
            <mrow> \ln\Big(0.1\Big) \amp =  t\cdot \ln\Big(0.7\Big)</mrow>
            <mrow>t \amp = \dfrac{ \ln\Big(0.1\Big)}{\ln\Big(0.7\Big)} = 6.45\dots</mrow>
          </md>
          It will take about 6.45 years for the balance to decline from 1000 to 100.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>


  
  <insight>
    <title>Depreciating Assets and Scrap Value</title>
    
    <p>
      In this class, our focus is on the mathematical tools that underly economics, business, and accounting.  
    </p>
    <p>
      In accounting, you will learn about how to decide which mathematical too to use (straight line versus declining balance depreciation), and to find a numerical value for the rate of depreciation. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Rates of depreciation can be found in many ways.  
      For example, you can use the actual sales price for cars based on their mileage to emperically determine how much the value drops per mile. 
    </p>
    <p>
      But there are also other ways of calculating the rate of depreciation. 
      For example, some assets have a known or conventional "scrap value" and "expected lifespan."
    </p>
    <p>
      Once you know the starting value, the scrap value, and the expected lifespan, you can actually compute the yearly depreciation you should use.  
      Mathematically, that means solving 
      <me>
        F = P ( 1- r)^t
      </me>
      for the rate <m>r</m> to get 
      <me>
        r = 1- \sqrt[t]{\frac{F}{P}}
      </me>
      
      
    </p>
    
  </insight>

